1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO THE AGRICULTURAL LAWS OF THIS
3 STATE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 AGRICULTURAL WATER PLAN UPDATE
7 SECTION 1.(a) The Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services shall update
8 the Strategic Plan for Protecting Agricultural Water Resources in North Carolina established in
9 S.L. 2010-149 to include all of the following:
10 (1) Water infrastructure needs to increase access and long-term storage capacity.
11 (2) Water conservation and reuse practices.
12 (3) Cost-share assistance needed to incentivize (i) construction of water
13 infrastructure to increase access and long-term storage capacity and (ii)
14 implementation of water conservation and reuse practices.
15 (4) Methods to identify best management practices for temporary water storage
16 and retention to mitigate downstream flooding.
17 (5) Methods to identify best management practices to reduce the impact of
18 flooding on agricultural lands.
19 (6) Methods to design incentive programs to compensate landowners that
20 participate in flood mitigation programs.
21 SECTION 1.(b) The Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services shall report
22 to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Agriculture and Natural and Economic
23 Resources by October 1, 2026, on the development of the plan and any legislative changes needed
24 to implement the plan.
25
26 FERAL SWINE WORKING GROUP
27 SECTION 2.(a) There is authorized and housed administratively within the Wildlife
28 Resources Commission the Feral Swine Working Group. The Working Group shall consist of
29 nine members, as follows:
30 (1) The Executive Director of the North Carolina Wildlife Resources
31 Commission or the Executive Director's designee, who shall serve as cochair.
32 (2) The Commissioner of Agriculture or the Commissioner's designee, who shall
33 serve as cochair.
34 (3) The Forest Supervisor of the United States Forest Service or the Forest
35 Supervisor's designee.
*S639-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) The State Director of the Wildlife Services Division of the Animal and Plant
2 Health Inspection Service of the United States Department of Agriculture or
3 the State Director's designee.
4 (5) A representative of the North Carolina Pork Council.
5 (6) A representative of the North Carolina Veterinary Medical Association.
6 (7) A representative of the North Carolina Cattlemen's Association.
7 (8) The President of the North Carolina Farm Bureau Federation, Inc., or the
8 President's designee.
9 (9) A representative of the North Carolina Wildlife Federation.
10 SECTION 2.(b) The Feral Swine Working Group shall develop a statewide plan to
11 control feral swine damage on private and public lands. The Feral Swine Working Group shall
12 act in an advisory capacity to the Wildlife Resources Commission. In developing the plan, the
13 Working Group shall do all of the following:
14 (1) Orient the plan primarily toward public health and safety and toward
15 landowner assistance, providing some relief to landowners through feral
16 swine control, management, and eradication.
17 (2) Develop a system for sharing data and information as well as documenting all
18 activities associated with feral swine damage control efforts, so as to facilitate
19 evaluation of efforts.
20 (3) Provide educational activities as a part of the program, such as printed
21 materials, on-site instructions, and local workshops.
22 (4) Provide for the hiring of personnel necessary to implement feral swine damage
23 control activities, administer the program, and set salaries of personnel.
24 SECTION 2.(c) No later than January 1 of each year, the Working Group shall issue
25 a report to the Wildlife Resources Commission, the Senate and House Appropriations
26 Subcommittees on Agriculture and Natural and Economic Resources, and the Fiscal Research
27 Division on the results of the program during the preceding year.
28 SECTION 2.(d) The Wildlife Resources Commission shall implement the plan and
29 may enter a cooperative agreement with the Wildlife Services Division of the Animal and Plant
30 Health Inspection Service, the United States Department of Agriculture, the North Carolina
31 Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services, and other relevant agencies or organizations
32 to accomplish the plan.
33
34 PROTECT LAND IN PERMANENT CONSERVATION EASEMENTS
35 SECTION 3. G.S. 160D-804 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
36 "(k) Protected Farm Tracts. – The regulation shall provide that if any boundary of the
37 proposed subdivision abuts one or more protected farm tracts, the applicant shall reserve a
38 vegetative buffer of at least 100 feet between the shared boundary of the land to be developed
39 and the residential lot or lots that would otherwise abut the protected farm tract or tracts. The
40 applicant shall indicate on the subdivision plat that the vegetative buffer has been set aside. For
41 the purpose of this subsection, "protected farm tract" means a tract of land that is subject to an
42 agricultural conservation easement as that term is defined in G.S. 106-744(b)."
43
