17 CLARIFY SPECIES SUSCEPTIBLE TO CHRONIC WASTING DISEASE
18 SECTION 8. G.S. 106-549.97 reads as rewritten:
19 "§ 106-549.97. Regulation by Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services of farmed
20 cervids produced and sold for commercial purposes; definitions.
21 (a) Repealed by Session Laws 2015-263, s. 14(a), effective September 30, 2015.
22 (a1) The following definitions apply in this Article:
23 (1) Commission. – The North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission.
24 (2) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Agriculture and Consumer
25 Services.
26 (3) Farmed Cervid. – Any cervid, as defined by the USDA Standards, that is
27 susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease, or any other member of the Cervidae
28 family that is not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease, that is held in
29 captivity and produced, bought, or sold for commercial purposes. Cervids that
30 are susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease are those set forth in 9 C.F.R. §
31 55.1. With regard to cervids that are susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease,
32 the term "farmed cervid" shall only include any cervid that was bred in
33 captivity and has been continuously maintained within a herd that is enrolled
34 in and complies with a USDA-approved Herd Certification Program. Any
35 animal registered or tagged in any licensed captive cervid facility existing
36 within the State as of July 1, 2015, is deemed to be a farmed cervid.
37 (4) Non-Farmed Cervid. – All animals in the family Cervidae other than farmed
38 cervids.
39 (5) USDA. – The United States Department of Agriculture.
40 (6) USDA Standards. – The United States Department of Agriculture's Chronic
41 Wasting Disease Program Standards, May 2014 edition, and subsequent
42 updates.
43 (a2) The Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services shall regulate the production,
44 sale, possession, and transportation, including importation and exportation, of farmed cervids.
45 The Department shall have sole authority with regard to farmed cervids, including administration
46 of the North Carolina Captive Cervid Herd Certification Program. The Department shall allow
47 the sale of farmed cervids, whether alive or dead, whole or in part, including, but not limited to,
48 the sale of antlers, antler velvet, hides, or meat from captive populations of farmed cervids. The
49 Department shall follow the USDA Standards and the provisions set forth in 9 C.F.R. Part 55 and
50 9 C.F.R. Part 81 in the implementation of this Article with regard to cervids susceptible to
51 Chronic Wasting Disease. The Department may adopt rules to implement this Article, including,
Page 4 Senate Bill 639-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 but not limited to, requirements for captivity licenses, captivity permits, transportation permits,
2 importation permits, and exportation permits. The Department may issue new captivity licenses
3 or permits for farmed cervid facilities that will hold cervids susceptible to Chronic Wasting
4 Disease only if Chronic Wasting Disease-susceptible source animals are from a certified herd in
5 accordance with USDA Standards from an existing licensed facility. Nothing in this section shall
6 limit the Department's ability to issue new captivity licenses and permits for farmed cervid
7 facilities that will hold cervids that are not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease. Any cervid
8 that is not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease as set forth in 9 C.F.R. § 55.1 may be imported
9 into the State to any licensed captive cervid facility. The Department shall not issue an
10 importation permit for any farmed cervid from a Chronic Wasting Disease-positive, exposed, or
11 suspect farmed cervid facility. Until such time as the USDA has adopted an approved method of
12 testing for Chronic Wasting Disease in living cervids, cervids susceptible to Chronic Wasting
13 Disease shall not be imported into North Carolina.
14 …."
