4 DACS LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER JURISDICTION
5 SECTION 17. G.S. 106-900 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 106-900. Powers of Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law-enforcement
7 officers.
8 (a) Authorization to Appoint. – The Commissioner is authorized to appoint as many
9 Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law enforcement officers as he or she deems
10 necessary to investigate and enforce any violation of the laws within the authority of the
11 Department or which occur on Department property. necessary. Such officers shall meet the
12 requirements of Article 1 of Chapter 17C of the General Statutes and shall take the oath of office
13 prescribed by Section 7 of Article VI of the North Carolina Constitution. Of these officers, the
14 Commissioner may designate certain officers to also have the powers and the duties of a forest
15 ranger enumerated in G.S. 106-898 and G.S. 106-899 and the power to enforce the forest laws.
16 A Department law enforcement officer may arrest, without warrant, any person or persons
17 committing any crime in the officer's presence or who such officer has probable cause for
18 believing has committed a crime in the officer's presence and bring such person or persons
19 forthwith before a district court or other officer having jurisdiction. Department law enforcement
20 officers shall also have authority to obtain and serve warrants including warrants for violation of
21 any duly promulgated rule of the Department.
22 (b) Territorial Jurisdiction. – A Department law enforcement officer is a State officer
23 with jurisdiction throughout the State, and beyond its boundaries to the extent provided by law,
24 in enforcing all matters within his or her respective subject matter jurisdiction as set forth in this
25 section.
26 (c) Subject Matter Jurisdiction. – After taking the oath described in subsection (a) of this
27 section, a Department law enforcement officer shall have the authority to arrest and take other
28 investigatory and enforcement actions for any criminal offense meeting any of the following
29 criteria:
30 (1) Occurring, encountered, or otherwise discovered on the premises of, or
31 elsewhere when the conduct relates to, property owned by, leased to, or
32 managed by the Department.
33 (2) Provided for under this Chapter, including the forest laws as set forth in
34 G.S. 106-897.
35 (3) Provided for in any duly adopted rule of the Department.
36 (4) Encountered or otherwise discovered while investigating or enforcing matters
37 for the Department or encountered or otherwise discovered while
38 investigating or enforcing the provisions of this Chapter, including the forest
39 laws as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
40 (5) Encountered or otherwise discovered while carrying out any duty or function
41 assigned to the Department by law.
42 (6) Occurring in a Department law enforcement officer's presence.
43 (7) Occurring outside of a Department law enforcement officer's presence as
44 provided in G.S. 15A-401(b), and for other offenses evincing a flouting of
45 their authority as enforcement officers or constituting a threat to public peace
46 and order which would tend to subvert the authority of the State if ignored. In
47 particular, Department law enforcement officers are authorized to arrest for
48 violations of G.S. 14-223, 14-225, 14-269, and 14-277.
49 (8) When assisting another law enforcement agency.
50 (d) Authority. – Department law enforcement officers have authority as peace officers to
51 do all of the following:
Page 10 Senate Bill 639-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Execute criminal process.
2 (2) Obtain and serve warrants, including arrest warrants, search warrants, orders
3 for arrest, criminal summonses, citations, subpoenas, and warrants for
4 violation of any duly adopted rule of the Department, and all other process
5 connected with any cases within their subject matter jurisdiction.
6 (3) Respond to and take enforcement action for any crime of violence or breach
7 of the peace.
8 (4) Any additional duties as may from time to time be directed by the
9 Commissioner when needed for security purposes at a public event or to
10 protect persons or property because of a disaster or state of emergency.
11 (e) Primary Responsibilities. – The primary law enforcement responsibility of a
12 Department law enforcement officer is the enforcement of this Chapter, including the forest laws
13 as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
14 (f) Service of Orders. – Department law enforcement officers have the authority to serve
15 and execute notices, orders, or demands issued by the Commissioner, the Department, or the
16 Board of Agriculture relating to any administrative proceeding. While serving and executing such
17 notices, orders, or demands, Department law enforcement officers shall have all of the power and
18 authority possessed by law enforcement officers when executing an arrest warrant.
19 (g) Temporary Stops. – Department law enforcement officers are authorized to stop
20 temporarily any persons they reasonably believe to be engaging in any activity regulated by the
21 Department to determine whether the activity is being conducted in compliance with the law,
22 including license and permitting requirements. Department law enforcement officers are also
23 authorized to see that the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes are enforced within
24 their jurisdiction and shall have the power to arrest on sight or upon warrant any motor vehicle
25 upon the highways of the State for the purpose of determining whether the motor vehicle is being
26 operated in violation of any of the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes. If the person
27 stopped is in a motor vehicle being driven at the time and the Department law enforcement officer
28 is also in a motor vehicle, the Department law enforcement officer shall sound a siren or activate
29 a special light, bell, horn, or exhaust whistle approved for law enforcement vehicles under
30 G.S. 20-125(b)."
31
32 INCREASE PENALTY FOR A SECOND OR SUBSEQUENT OFFENSE FOR
33 LARCENY OF CROPS
34 SECTION 18.(a) G.S. 14-78 reads as rewritten:
35 "§ 14-78. Larceny of ungathered crops.
36 (a) If It is unlawful for any person shall to steal or feloniously take and carry away any
37 maize, corn, wheat, rice or other grain, or any cotton, tobacco, potatoes, peanuts, pulse, fruit,
38 vegetable or other product cultivated for food or market, growing, standing or remaining
39 ungathered in any field or ground, that person is guilty of a Class H felony.ground.
40 (b) A violation of this section is punishable as follows:
41 (1) For a first offense under this section, the person is guilty of a Class H felony,
42 punishable by a fine of not less than two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) in
43 addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense.
44 (2) For a second or subsequent offense under this section, the person is guilty of
45 a Class G felony, punishable by a fine of not less than five hundred dollars
46 ($500.00) in addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense."
47 SECTION 18.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
48 offenses committed on or after that date.
49
50 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE AND EFFECTIVE DATE
